paragraphs.title: Generate Data and Verify Ingestion
paragraphs.text:
%sh
# Generate syslog messages by trying to ssh to the namenode unit.
# This will likely result in a 'publickey denied' error, but it will
# be enough to trigger a syslog event on the namenode.
MASTER=`grep slave-1 /etc/hosts | awk '{print $1}'`
for i in `seq 1 10`;
do
  ssh -oStrictHostKeyChecking=no $MASTER uptime >/dev/null 2>&1
  sleep 1
done

# Check if Flume has collected and sent the syslog messages to HDFS.
# If no output is seen from this command, wait a few minutes and try
# again. The amount of time between Flume ingesting the event and it
# being available in HDFS is controlled by the 'roll_interval'
# configuration option in the flume-hdfs charm.
hadoop fs -ls -R /user/flume/flume-syslog | tail

import org.joda.time.DateTime
import org.joda.time.format.{DateTimeFormatterBuilder, DateTimeFormat}
import scala.util.Try
val reSystemLog = """^\<\d+\>([A-Za-z0-9, ]+\d{2}:\d{2}:\d{2}(?:\.\d{3})?)\s+(\S+)\s+([^\[]+)\[(\d+)\]\s*:?\s*(.*)""".r
case class SyslogMessage(timestamp: String, host: Option[String], process: String, pid: Int, message: String, username: String)

val lines = sc.textFile("/user/flume/flume-syslog/*/*.txt").filter(line => line.contains("input_userauth_request"))
val events = lines.flatMap {
      case reSystemLog(timestamp,hostname, proc, pidS, msg) =>
        val username: String = msg.mkString("")
        val realuser = username.split(" ")
        for {pid <- Try(pidS.toInt).toOption} yield SyslogMessage(timestamp,Some(hostname), proc, pid, msg, realuser(3))
      case _ => None
    }.toDF()

events.registerTempTable("syslogusers")
